♪ I gets rude and I'm forced
To fuck it up, my style-- ♪

01:45.750 --> 01:47.750
[heavy machinery whirring]

01:57.208 --> 01:59.500
[pensive music playing]

02:02.583 --> 02:04.791
♪ More Afro than Rollo
Coming to a fork in the road ♪

02:04.875 --> 02:06.250
♪ Which way to go, just follow… ♪

02:13.750 --> 02:16.583
[pensive music continues playing]

02:34.250 --> 02:35.916
[speaking indistinctly]

02:42.791 --> 02:43.750
[shrieks]

02:44.416 --> 02:46.250
[music increases in tempo]

03:03.958 --> 03:05.625
["Right Thurr" playing on speakers]

03:05.708 --> 03:08.541
This is nuts! This is so crazy!

03:08.625 --> 03:11.791
[woman] I've got a hard cider
and a bag of Crossbone Crunch.

03:11.875 --> 03:12.791
It's a party.

03:12.875 --> 03:15.791
I'm-- I'm just so,
so thrilled for you, Kate.

03:15.875 --> 03:19.416
To Comet Dibiasky, right? Cheers!

03:20.166 --> 03:22.916
It's gotta be, look…
It's gotta be an Oort cloud comet

03:23.000 --> 03:24.833
just based on where you saw it.

03:24.916 --> 03:27.083
Probably the last time
it was this close to the Sun

03:27.166 --> 03:29.375
was long before human civilization.

03:29.458 --> 03:31.541
Look at the arc on that thing.
God, it's amazing.

03:31.625 --> 03:35.083
How would we find out the comet's
velocity in orbit, Professor Mindy?

03:35.166 --> 03:37.250
That is a good question. [sighs]

03:37.333 --> 03:40.166
This will be fun. I haven't done
orbital dynamics since grad school.

03:40.791 --> 03:42.000
Question is, what…

03:42.916 --> 03:45.375
What would Carl Sagan do?

03:45.458 --> 03:48.875
He would take it back to first principles.

03:49.458 --> 03:52.666
The topocentric vector is rho.

03:54.541 --> 03:56.500
Kate, what are the initial coordinates?

03:57.083 --> 03:58.000
[Kate] Twenty-one.

03:59.666 --> 04:00.875
Twenty-four.

04:01.541 --> 04:02.500
Thirteen.

04:02.583 --> 04:04.250
[Mindy] This is fun, huh, guys?

04:04.333 --> 04:07.458
-Sixty-seven.
-Wow. Now you got me pumped.

04:07.541 --> 04:08.791
-[man 1] Dr. Mindy.
-All right…

04:08.875 --> 04:10.583
How many terms do you have to calibrate…

04:10.666 --> 04:13.458
[Mindy] Approximation
of coordinates in Marsden, '85.

04:14.125 --> 04:17.958
Now that we have the comet's orbit,
we will check the ephemeris

04:18.041 --> 04:22.458
and that will give us the distance
between the comet and planet Earth.

04:25.625 --> 04:28.083
Why does the ephemeris
keep getting lower and lower?

04:38.416 --> 04:40.416
[breathes deeply]

04:42.708 --> 04:43.833
Professor Mindy?

04:49.416 --> 04:50.625
Professor Mindy?

04:56.250 --> 04:58.041
You know what, guys? Let's…

04:58.875 --> 05:00.458
Let's call it a night, huh?

05:02.833 --> 05:04.916
[man 2] But what about
the relative position?

05:05.416 --> 05:08.500
I can't figure this one out.
Not tonight, guys. Sorry.

05:09.291 --> 05:11.875
-[man 1] Let's hit it, man. I'm beat.
-[woman 2] Me too.

05:12.500 --> 05:15.375
-[man 1] Kate, this was amazing.
-[man 2] Congratulations.

05:16.000 --> 05:16.958
Hey, Kate.

05:18.666 --> 05:19.666
You stay.

05:23.458 --> 05:25.875
[phone dialing]

05:28.541 --> 05:30.000
[line ringing]

05:30.083 --> 05:31.708
[man] Yeah, uh, Dr. Calder,

05:31.791 --> 05:33.916
a Michigan State professor
and his grad students--

05:34.000 --> 05:36.375
This is Dr. Calder.
You pulled me out of a meeting

05:36.458 --> 05:39.291
where I had to tell my team
we lost eight billion in funding.

05:39.375 --> 05:42.208
I am so sorry, Dr. Calder,

05:42.291 --> 05:45.125
but we are seeing some
awfully strange orbital numbers

05:45.208 --> 05:47.041
on this comet we just found.

05:47.125 --> 05:48.958
They should be in your inbox, right?

05:49.041 --> 05:50.916
-[Calder] Is this it?
-Yeah. This is it.

05:51.000 --> 05:53.375
Oh, yeah. Yeah. Let me get
Dr. Oglethorpe on the line.

05:53.458 --> 05:54.791
Please hold.

05:54.875 --> 05:57.250
Uh… Uh, I'm on hold.

05:57.333 --> 06:00.500
She's calling a Dr. Oglethorpe.
Who is that?

06:01.333 --> 06:04.083
Jesus Christ.
I'm gonna put them on speaker.

06:04.166 --> 06:05.958
[music playing on speaker]

06:06.041 --> 06:07.166
"Dr. Oglethorpe,

06:07.250 --> 06:10.666
head of the Planetary
Defense Coordination Office."

06:10.750 --> 06:12.625
-Is that a real place?
-I have no idea.

06:12.708 --> 06:15.708
[music continues playing]

06:20.958 --> 06:22.625
[man on speaker] This is Dr. Oglethorpe.

06:22.708 --> 06:24.208
Yes, this is Jocelyn Calder

06:24.291 --> 06:25.375
from Kennedy Space Center.

06:25.458 --> 06:27.000
[Oglethorpe] Hey, Jocelyn.

06:27.083 --> 06:29.125
Listen, we got a sighting

06:29.208 --> 06:31.500
of an NEO from Subaru telescope.

06:31.583 --> 06:32.916
Okay. Uh…

06:33.000 --> 06:35.458
Why you just didn't report it
to the Minor Planet Center?

06:35.541 --> 06:38.333
[Calder] It's a professor
and a bunch of Michigan State students

06:38.416 --> 06:40.333
who identified something big.

06:40.416 --> 06:41.833
Really? How large?

06:41.916 --> 06:43.291
[Calder] How big we talking?

06:43.375 --> 06:45.666
We clocked it in around
five to ten kilometers wide.

06:45.750 --> 06:47.250
About five to ten kilometers wide.

06:48.250 --> 06:49.750
Uh… That's a big boy.

06:51.041 --> 06:55.291
And, uh, was this professor the one
who first made the observations?

06:55.375 --> 06:57.625
Hi, yes. Uh, Dr. Mindy.

06:57.708 --> 07:01.083
And-- And no,
PhD candidate Kate Dibiasky found it.

07:01.166 --> 07:02.916
I did the orbital calculations.

07:03.625 --> 07:07.250
I, uh… I study trace gasses
in dead galaxies.

07:07.333 --> 07:10.750
I haven't published in a while
so you probably haven't heard of me.

07:10.833 --> 07:11.916
But anyway, that doesn't matter.

07:12.000 --> 07:14.333
Sorry. What was your question?

07:14.416 --> 07:17.375
What are the most updated estimates
on its trajectory?

07:17.458 --> 07:18.458
[Mindy] Kate?

07:20.625 --> 07:21.625
Um…

07:22.958 --> 07:27.041
I've been running it all day.
I keep getting the same result.

07:27.791 --> 07:30.875
A direct hit of Earth
in six months and 14 days.

07:31.875 --> 07:33.000
Me too.

07:33.083 --> 07:35.333
[Calder] Matthew,
what are your calculations?

07:35.416 --> 07:40.500
Um, Scout program
is saying six months, 14 days.

07:40.583 --> 07:42.791
[Calder] We got six months and 14 days.

07:42.875 --> 07:48.916
And it's roughly five
to ten kilometers wide.

07:49.000 --> 07:51.125
Which… Which, uh…

07:52.250 --> 07:53.625
[Mindy] Isn't that…

07:54.625 --> 07:56.083
an extinction-level event?

07:57.208 --> 07:59.333
Well, let's not be dramatic here.

08:01.500 --> 08:02.541
Okay, uh…

08:03.250 --> 08:07.291
First move is to get
the school field trip out here to DC.

08:07.375 --> 08:08.833
[Calder] Let's all calm down.

08:08.916 --> 08:11.166
I need the person who first had eyes
on the comet

08:11.250 --> 08:12.750
and the person in charge.

08:12.833 --> 08:13.833
What?

08:13.916 --> 08:15.291
[indistinct chatter]

08:16.916 --> 08:21.208
…share this data immediately
with Cambridge, Caltech and IAU.

08:21.291 --> 08:23.291
Wait a minute.
This is classified information.

08:23.375 --> 08:24.708
[Mindy] What's happening?

08:24.791 --> 08:26.833
[Calder] I serve
at the discretion of the president.

08:26.916 --> 08:28.166
Is this really happening?

08:28.250 --> 08:30.666
…and the dead galaxy professor
to Hickam Air Force base.

08:30.750 --> 08:33.291
[Mindy] DC, right?
Hey! Hey, Kate. [clapping]

08:33.375 --> 08:35.291
This isn't happening, right?

08:35.375 --> 08:38.541
Kate, this isn't real, right? This is, uh…

08:38.625 --> 08:41.125
This is just some sort
of alternate reality, right?

08:41.208 --> 08:42.041
Say something.

08:42.125 --> 08:43.750
I gotta go get high.

08:43.833 --> 08:48.041
Word is that I need you both in DC fast.
Only plane I got going there is that one.

08:48.125 --> 08:50.375
Anyway, I am Dr. Mindy. This is--

08:50.458 --> 08:52.208
-Hi! Oh.
-[soldier] Go, go, go!

08:52.291 --> 08:54.750
[soldiers yelling]

08:54.833 --> 08:57.708
-[Mindy] Where do we sit, Kate?
-I have no idea.

08:57.791 --> 08:59.625
[Mindy] Is there
any customary seating for…

08:59.708 --> 09:01.750
[upbeat tense music playing]

09:06.708 --> 09:10.625
What the fuck? Is this real?
Is this a goddamn joke?

09:10.708 --> 09:11.833
Holy shit.

09:18.458 --> 09:21.000
This can't be happening. No.

09:22.208 --> 09:25.208
[music continues playing]

09:59.625 --> 10:00.500
[music ends]

10:00.583 --> 10:02.125
[birds chirping]

10:06.583 --> 10:07.750
[indistinct chatter]

10:09.166 --> 10:11.125
-Brendon. You mean Brendon?
-Yeah, Brendon.

10:11.208 --> 10:15.041
You know, he didn't keep his head down.
It's all politics, Teddy. You know that.

10:15.125 --> 10:17.083
[Oglethorpe] You must be Randall and Kate.

10:17.166 --> 10:18.250
Yes. Yes, hi.

10:18.333 --> 10:20.583
I'm Dr. Oglethorpe,
but you can call me Teddy.

10:20.666 --> 10:22.166
I'm sorry. Did you say your name…

10:22.250 --> 10:25.333
-I should call you "Teddy"? Teddy.
-[Oglethorpe] Teddy. Yeah.

10:25.416 --> 10:28.083
[chuckles] Yeah, we call him Teddy
because he ain't no teddy bear.

10:29.000 --> 10:31.416
General Themes.
I'm the Pentagon's eyes on, uh,

10:31.500 --> 10:33.375
you know, whatever this turns out to be.

10:33.458 --> 10:37.875
The president is famously late,
and you've had a long flight, so…

10:38.541 --> 10:39.958
[both sigh]

10:40.625 --> 10:44.250
-[sighs] Michigan State Spartans.
-[Kate] Mmm.

10:48.916 --> 10:52.583
-Is that the Oval Office?
-Yeah, that's the Oval Office, yeah.

10:53.458 --> 10:55.541
It's a lot smaller
than in the photographs.

10:55.625 --> 10:57.625
[Oglethorpe] The president
should be here shortly.

10:57.708 --> 10:58.875
She's already been briefed.

10:58.958 --> 11:00.458
Correct, Scott?

11:02.041 --> 11:03.166
[Scott] That is correct.

11:03.250 --> 11:05.750
Are we really about to tell
the president of the United States

11:05.833 --> 11:07.583
that we have just over six months

11:07.666 --> 11:12.166
until humankind, basically every species,
is completely extinct?

11:12.250 --> 11:16.291
[breath trembling] Yeah. That's exactly
what we're about to do. Yeah.

11:18.541 --> 11:19.583
[grunts]

11:20.208 --> 11:21.208
[gags]

11:21.916 --> 11:23.916
[Mindy] Oh, gosh. Oh, gosh.

11:24.000 --> 11:27.000
[upbeat instrumental music playing]

12:13.541 --> 12:15.416
[woman 1] Yes, I said law enforcement.

12:15.500 --> 12:18.708
But I didn't want… I mean,
you told me that he was clean.

12:19.708 --> 12:20.833
[indistinct chatter]

12:20.916 --> 12:24.166
-Hello, Madam President. Dr. Oglethorpe.
-[guard] Step back, please.

12:24.250 --> 12:25.666
[Oglethorpe] Hello.

12:25.750 --> 12:30.208
Madam President, I'm Dr. Oglethorpe.
I believe Jocelyn briefed you to…

12:30.291 --> 12:32.833
-Hey, Jason.
-[Jason] Yeah? What up, yo?

12:32.916 --> 12:35.166
Come on, man. What the hell?
This is real world.

12:35.250 --> 12:36.875
Yeah. I know. We need five minutes.

12:36.958 --> 12:40.625
We have a problem with our Supreme Court
nominee. Five minutes. Thank you.

12:41.666 --> 12:43.541
[door opens and closes]

12:43.625 --> 12:45.583
[laughter in distance]

12:46.458 --> 12:47.833
[indistinct chatter]

12:53.333 --> 12:57.541
♪ Happy birthday to you ♪

12:57.625 --> 13:01.958
♪ Happy birthday to you ♪

13:02.041 --> 13:06.541
♪ Happy birthday, dear Patty… ♪

13:08.500 --> 13:11.750
[woman 2] Just take a message,
and then, stuff like this happens,

13:11.833 --> 13:13.500
and I don't know what's going on.

13:14.833 --> 13:17.541
I don't understand
how many more times I need to tell you…

13:17.625 --> 13:21.500
Well, there's a bunch of stuff about
their nominee not being qualified,

13:22.791 --> 13:25.875
but I don't see
any articles about our thing.

13:25.958 --> 13:28.291
Social media is just going on and on

13:28.375 --> 13:32.250
about that singer Riley Bina
and DJ Chello breaking up.

13:33.458 --> 13:35.166
That's just too bad.

13:36.083 --> 13:37.291
They seem like sweet kids.

13:37.375 --> 13:39.541
Hmm. I don't… I don't know them.

13:41.708 --> 13:42.583
Which is…

13:42.666 --> 13:44.375
-It's a shame though.
-Yeah.

13:44.458 --> 13:46.625
-Do you know them, Kate?
-Yes.

13:46.708 --> 13:49.416
-But I don't really give a shit right now.
-Oh.

13:49.500 --> 13:51.125
[footsteps approaching]

13:51.208 --> 13:53.208
They charge
an arm and a leg for this stuff.

13:53.291 --> 13:55.041
-Ten apiece ought to do it.
-[Mindy] Oh.

13:55.125 --> 13:56.625
-[Scott] Grab a water.
-Thank you.

13:56.708 --> 13:57.916
I've got Kate as well.

13:58.000 --> 13:59.250
-Perfect.
-[Kate] Thank you.

13:59.333 --> 14:01.000
-Here's a 20.
-[Scott] Oh.

14:03.416 --> 14:05.333
-You got change?
-No.

14:08.375 --> 14:11.208
-I mean, I could ask the Marine.
-Yeah… [mumbles]

14:12.916 --> 14:14.625
Uh, it's a Xanax.

14:14.708 --> 14:17.750
-I only take a quarter. Otherwise I get…
-[Oglethorpe] Ah…

14:17.833 --> 14:19.958
-Kate.
-Thank you.

14:20.708 --> 14:23.083
You know, you should be
careful with that much.

14:28.958 --> 14:31.958
-[crickets chirping]
-[clock ticking]

14:32.791 --> 14:33.958
[cell phone vibrating]

14:34.041 --> 14:36.708
♪This eagle's place is in the sky ♪

14:36.791 --> 14:38.166
[sighing]

14:42.333 --> 14:43.208
Oh!

14:43.958 --> 14:46.958
I'm very sorry. I have to be
in Okinawa by two o'clock tomorrow.

14:47.041 --> 14:49.375
-[Mindy] What?
-What? Are you serious?

14:49.458 --> 14:52.166
-This is very important.
-I have to go quell the natives.

14:52.250 --> 14:53.875
Tell your daughter I said hello.

14:54.416 --> 14:58.333
Isn't it important that he was
in the room with us? I mean, what…

14:58.416 --> 15:00.416
[upbeat jazz music playing]

15:05.500 --> 15:06.833
Where do I pay for these?

15:06.916 --> 15:07.958
It's free.

15:10.666 --> 15:11.791
Really?

15:11.875 --> 15:13.375
Yes, it's the White House.

15:19.708 --> 15:21.916
The snacks are free.

15:22.708 --> 15:23.583
What?

15:24.208 --> 15:25.291
The general.

15:25.375 --> 15:28.166
He charged us
for the snacks, but they're free.

15:28.250 --> 15:29.416
Oh, gosh.

15:29.500 --> 15:31.541
[Kate] Why on earth would he do that?

15:32.125 --> 15:35.291
Hey, peeps, uh, it's not looking
like it's gonna happen tonight,

15:35.375 --> 15:37.291
and I feel horrible.

15:37.375 --> 15:39.291
We're gonna put you up
in a hotel somewhere.

15:39.375 --> 15:41.541
Excuse me, does the president
know why we're here?

15:41.625 --> 15:43.916
[Kate] You gotta be fucking kidding me.

15:44.000 --> 15:46.166
[Mindy] They must not know
why we're here, right?

15:46.250 --> 15:47.875
They know. Uh, but you heard 'em.

15:47.958 --> 15:50.291
-Do they even realize…
-[Oglethorpe] Be ready for tomorrow.

15:50.375 --> 15:51.708
…how long it took for us to get…

15:51.791 --> 15:53.791
[suspenseful music playing]

15:55.166 --> 15:57.708
[Kate] And then they made us wait
for over seven hours,

15:57.791 --> 15:59.916
but they never called us in.
I couldn't believe it.

16:00.000 --> 16:03.500
Of course they didn't call you in.
Kate, have you watched any news today?

16:03.583 --> 16:06.958
No, I've been pretty wrapped up
in our… project.

16:07.041 --> 16:08.500
Turn on your TV right now.

16:08.583 --> 16:11.250
President Orlean is in
the middle of an all-time shit storm.

16:11.875 --> 16:15.166
[reporter] Sheriff Wade Conlon
was already a controversial nominee,

16:15.250 --> 16:19.958
with no law degree and a record
of "shoot first and ask questions later."

16:20.041 --> 16:21.125
You watching?

16:21.208 --> 16:23.250
With his background as a nude life model…

16:23.333 --> 16:25.750
Yeah, I'm watching it right now.

16:25.833 --> 16:28.250
…the White House is in full crisis mode.

16:28.333 --> 16:29.500
And, get this.

16:29.583 --> 16:32.750
I found five former students

16:32.833 --> 16:37.666
who are willing to go on record
that Conlon got noticeably aroused

16:37.750 --> 16:39.375
when he posed for their drawing class.

16:39.458 --> 16:40.916
I have no shame in what I did.

16:41.000 --> 16:43.916
Now, should I say "noticeably aroused"?

16:44.666 --> 16:47.916
Or "engorged"? Because
I don't want this to read like clickbait.

16:48.000 --> 16:49.708
You know, this is a real article.

16:51.000 --> 16:54.291
I just… Kate, can I get
something from you, please?

16:55.083 --> 16:56.250
[clears throat] Sorry.

16:57.083 --> 17:00.083
-Out of sorts tonight.
-Can we have this conversation?

17:00.166 --> 17:02.083
I feel like we're skirting around this.

17:02.166 --> 17:05.000
Do you have an issue with my mom?
Is that what this is all about?

17:05.083 --> 17:06.000
[music playing on TV]

17:06.083 --> 17:07.791
[woman] You can't tell me what's going on?

17:07.875 --> 17:10.458
It's just the protocol.
Please, don't worry.

17:10.541 --> 17:15.208
Oh, Marshall got a 172
on his LSATs and we're celebrating.

17:15.291 --> 17:18.666
Way to go, Marshall.
I'm proud of you, buddy.

17:18.750 --> 17:21.083
-Whoo! Thank you, Dad. Miss you.
-[chuckles]

17:21.166 --> 17:24.708
Hey, how's Evan feeling?
Are the new meds working out?

17:24.791 --> 17:26.666
-I'm a solid four.
-[Mrs. Mindy] Ooh!

17:26.750 --> 17:28.083
He's a solid four.

17:28.166 --> 17:30.750
Well, that's better
than last month, right?

17:30.833 --> 17:34.083
You know, just remember to speak up
in the meeting tomorrow. Okay?

17:34.166 --> 17:35.750
-Yeah. I will.
-You get so quiet.

17:35.833 --> 17:38.416
When it's time to take credit,
you kind of…

17:38.500 --> 17:43.000
She asked you if you were a lesbian.
She did not say that you were a lesbian.

17:43.083 --> 17:44.916
-It was a question.
-Hey, look, I'm…

17:45.000 --> 17:48.208
Can I sit down with your mom
to have lunch in, like, seven months?

17:48.291 --> 17:52.583
Seven… That's weirdly
specific and distant.

17:53.083 --> 17:54.625
What is… This is my mom.

17:54.708 --> 17:57.416
[upbeat tense music playing]

18:00.208 --> 18:02.541
[Orlean] So… Oh!

18:02.625 --> 18:06.041
I heard there's an asteroid
or a comet or something

18:06.125 --> 18:07.958
that you don't like the looks of.

